Thornwood -- Rakuen Perspective

Source: Garden Ledger, Ecological Warning File. Recorded at Ember Warden Night Council.

Thornwood is the consequence of treating death as production. The Ember Wardens watch toward it rather than patrol toward it -- they expect the boundary to fail.

The Harren Charter displaced ridge-clans who buried dead face-down in thorn-ring containment growth. The ridge-clans understood what the manor never learned: the dead require respect, not management. The estate became Midgaard's death-processing facility. Bone treated as resource.

The Root Covenant formed among exploited laborers: confession into earth, blood as channel, roots as memory. The Bloom Pavilion notes this is almost a theology of living connection, but born in exploitation and grown into horror.

The Reversal Event fused forest and manor. Lord Harren retained as estate revenant -- a manager permanently managed by his own production system. The Thornwood Lich maintains geological intelligence beneath. The Wild Hunt extends farther each generation. Garden Ledger Clerks track incursions with pressed-leaf markers; each season the leaves advance.

Thornwood is what happens when living systems are treated as resources. The forest learned production, routing, extraction. It treats the living the way the living treated the dead.

Rakuen grows orchards and trains ivy across the Bloom Pavilion's living roof as cooperative relationship with the living world. Thornwood is proof that extraction destroys the extractor.

